    "A parallel debate looks at whether electoral polls-or sometimes exit polls specifically-are morally justified (Michalos 1991; Sonderholm 2016; Thompson 2008).",
    "We will not consider all arguments against polls-Michalos highlights no less than sixteen arguments on behalf of banning the publication of poll results.",
    "However, we want to stress that the objections we consider are in no way novel; instead, they are exacerbated by the transition to AI polling.",
    "Looking at the specific case of exit polls, Sonderholm critically assesses \"the being-influenced-by-how-otherpeople-vote-is-a-bad-thing argument\" (what we call more succinctly the 'autonomy objection'), the strategic voting argument (what we call the 'tactical voting objection') and the 'potentially misleading information argument', which relates to our 'manipulation objection'.",
    "The objections are not new, but they become more pressing with the frequency and granularity of AI polling-as we explain at length later, it becomes possible to know much more precisely what others think and which group thinks what and to assess whether it is worth voting tactically."
